content:
A lot of the result of fundamentalist belief systems is clarifying who the enemy is: &ldquo;Who are we supposed to be fighting now?&rdquo;
It sometimes feels inevitable. Like a default state, it&rsquo;s not &ldquo;Should we be fighting?&rdquo; It&rsquo;s &ldquo;who?&rdquo;
For example, in that podcast conversation, Weiss gave us a couple targets to fight (&ldquo;the Bernie bros on the left and the Trump apologists on the right&rdquo;) while admonishing fundamentalism.
So let&rsquo;s ask the other question that doesn&rsquo;t get asked, &ldquo;Should we be fighting?&rdquo;

Which brings us to &ldquo;Is war inevitable? Is a war mentality necessary to fix the problems of the world?&rdquo;
To answer those question, read this:
   ESSAY: The End of War / Charles Eisenstein

Yascha said:
 &ldquo;They want to have one creed that allows them to prejudge the world&hellip; It allows you to enter any conversation people are having around you that isn&rsquo;t being had on those exact terms, and to identify: (A) you guys are all fallow because you aren&rsquo;t seeing the world for what it is. And (B) I&rsquo;m actually far superior, because&hellip;&rdquo;
 He continues:
 &ldquo;There are a couple of simple terms you use, and it allows you to be on the vanguard of history, morally righteous, and super smart very easily. Without any actual thought.&rdquo;
 Talk through this with someone (or your journal): What do you think about what Yascha said? Does this explain some of the spread of SJD to you? Give a glimpse into why so many people advance our particular form of fundamentalism? What does it not explain? What about his summary concerns you, or do you think is unhelpful?

What&rsquo;s great about this idea is that in that conversation, it plays out immediately after Yascha shares it, proving its viability in real time.
If you keep listening, you&rsquo;ll hear Sam Harris, the podcast host, weigh in to echo Yascha&rsquo;s point, summing it up as an &ldquo;unfalsifiable trump card you can play that meets the demand of any occasion.&rdquo;
And then something magical happens. The other podcast guest, Michael Weiss, jumps in, thinking he&rsquo;s adding to Yascha&rsquo;s point, completely oblivious that he&rsquo;s actually proving it.
Weiss says, talking of the fundamentalists who take the &ldquo;high ground&rdquo; in Yascha&rsquo;s example:
 &ldquo;Belonging to a political or social movement gives them a sense of purpose. We see this on Twitter. The campism is so codified and narrowly defined: we have Bernie Bros on the left, MAGA Trump apologists on the right, and then trying to navigate with any sense of independent-mindedness at all makes you a target for everybody.&rdquo;
 In that reply, Weiss delivers to us a slurry of simple terms, regurgitated from his position (that lots of people, particularly &ldquo;online&rdquo; people share) without much thinking, that unfalsifiably sum up the &ldquo;bad&rdquo; people and position himself as morally virtuous, on the high ground.
Yascha replies, politely calling our attention to this:
 &ldquo;The anti-woke left crowd can fall foul of the same problem, so it&rsquo;s something we all need to check ourselves on as well.&rdquo;
 So true! And no shame on Weiss here. We&rsquo;re just pointing out that it&rsquo;s such an easy trap to fall into that Weiss did it while thinking he&rsquo;s talking about the trap &ndash; a trap many of us fall into every day.

In the paper, Nagata goes further, drawing on a pile of disparate sources to provide a snapshot of the mindset of fundamentalism.
Here&rsquo;s the relevant quote from the abstract:
 &ldquo;It also reflects a mind‐set uncompromising and antirelativist, as one response to the openness and uncertainties of a cosmopolitan world, and to chart a morally black and white path out of the gray zones of intimidating cultural and religious complexity.&rdquo;

One of the projects of social justice minus dogma is going to be tearing down the wall. Expanding our idea of &ldquo;us.&rdquo;
The distinction between a paradox and a contradiction, within the context of fundamentalism, is one of the walls that creates an &ldquo;us&rdquo; and &ldquo;them.&rdquo; We laugh, or turn up our noses, when They don&rsquo;t see the truth of a paradox. &ldquo;How simple-minded. How backwards. How unenlightened.&rdquo;
Let&rsquo;s nudge toward dismantling the wall by naming some of the ideas we might be accepting as paradoxes, but likely seem to be contradictions to people outside of SJD, creating room for that truth.
📝Journal: What paradoxes have you noticed within SJD? Within the cornerstones, the tenets, or the ways that we enact fundamentalism? What does it feel like to encounter a paradox?
